@@ -0,0 +1,57 @@
+# re_video_g2g
+
+A [glass2glass](https://github.com/Glass2GlassHQ) hardware **Vulkan Video** decode
+backend for `re_video`, kept out of tree as the reference implementer of
+`re_video`'s hardware-decode extension point.
+
+`re_video` exposes a small, backend-agnostic registry
+(`re_video::register_hw_video_decoder`) and a GPU-resident frame shape
+(`re_video::GpuVideoFrame`, behind the `gpu-textures` feature). This crate registers
+a factory against it; `re_video::new_decoder` then prefers g2g's hardware decoder for
+H.264 / H.265 / AV1 whenever a Vulkan decode device is available, and falls back to
+`re_video`'s built-in software decoders otherwise. **`re_video` has no dependency on
+this crate or on glass2glass** — the coupling is one directional, which is the whole
+point of the split: the extension point is vendor-neutral and upstreamable, the g2g
+binding lives here.
+
+## Two output tiers
+
+- **Tier A (readback):** g2g decodes on the GPU (vendor-neutral Vulkan Video), reads
+  the frame back as packed I420, and hands it to `re_video`, which uploads it and
+  does YUV->RGB in `re_renderer`.
+- **Tier B (zero-copy):** g2g keeps the frame GPU-resident and hands `re_video` the
+  decoded `wgpu::Texture` directly (YUV->RGB already applied on the decode device) as
+  a `GpuVideoFrame` on `FrameContent::gpu_texture`. `re_renderer` renders it with no
+  CPU readback and no colour convert. Select with `set_prefer_gpu_textures(true)`.
+
+## Usage
+
+```rust
+re_video_g2g::register();                    // once at startup
+// re_video_g2g::set_prefer_gpu_textures(true); // opt into Tier B (zero-copy)
+let decoder = re_video::new_decoder(name, &video, &settings, sender)?;
+```
+
+## Device identity (Tier B)
+
+A `wgpu::Texture` is bound to the device it was created on. g2g creates the decode
+device itself (it needs Vulkan video-decode queue families a render-only device
+omits), so the correct direction is for the renderer to run **on the decode device**:
+build `re_renderer::RenderContext` from the `GpuVideoFrame`'s carried
+`adapter`/`device`/`queue`. On a host whose display GPU differs from the decode GPU a
+cross-device copy is unavoidable; use Tier A there.
+
+The g2g `wgpu` (29.x) and Rerun's workspace `wgpu` (29.0) resolve to a single crate
+version, so the decoded texture handle crosses into `re_video::GpuVideoFrame` with no
+copy. If those ever diverge to semver-incompatible majors, Tier B stops compiling.
+
+## Tests
+
+The integration tests (`tests/`) run on the RTX 3060 and skip gracefully with no
+Vulkan decode adapter / no distinct compute queue. They decode the shared fixtures
+under `../re_video/tests/fixtures/` and check bit-exactness against a software ffmpeg
+`yuv420p` reference:
+
+```sh
+cargo +stable test -p re_video_g2g --release
+```
